<h1 id="lecture-content-questions">Lecture Content Questions</h1>

<p><a href="Content_Part1.md"><strong>1</strong></a>
Which type of visualization would be <em>best suited</em> to look at a frequency distribution?</p>

<ul>
  <li>Scatter plot</li>
  <li>Pie chart</li>
  <li>Histogram</li>
  <li>Bar chart</li>
  <li>Box plot</li>
  <li>Line plot</li>
  <li>Cartogram</li>
</ul>

<p><a href="Content_Part1.md"><strong>2</strong></a>
When a histogram shows a long tail with a handful of outliers, we say the distribution is skewed because deviates from the <strong>__</strong>_ distribution.</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part1.md"><strong>3</strong></a>
Which unsupervised map classification method in ArcGIS Pro will usually provide you with the best results?</p>

<ul>
  <li>Defined interval</li>
  <li>Equal interval</li>
  <li>Natural breaks</li>
  <li>Manual breaks</li>
</ul>

<p><a href="Content_Part1.md"><strong>4</strong></a>
Supervised classification methods are always better than unsupervised because humans are smarter than computers. [T/F]</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part1.md"><strong>5</strong></a>
Unsupervised classification methods require no input from the user, the computer does all the work. [T/F]</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>6</strong></a>
Briefly, explain the differences between Supervised and Unsupervised classification methods.</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part1.md"><strong>7</strong></a>
Random forests require a user to provide <strong>__</strong>_ classes.</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>8</strong></a>
It is important to avoid using sequential color pallets or graduated symbols for _____ data because they can imply a ranking/direction, even though this type of data has no rank/direction.</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>9</strong></a>
Diverging color maps are great for showing deviations from a mean value. [T/F]</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>10</strong></a>
Sequential color maps use gradations of different shades (light/dark) of the same color. [T/F]</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>11</strong></a>
The best maps pack the most amount of information into the least amount of space. [T/F]</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>12</strong></a>
Every map should always have a north arrow. [T/F]</p>

<p><a href="Content_Part2.md"><strong>13</strong></a>
This type of colorblindness impacts ~ 4.5% of the human population.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Red-Green</li>
  <li>Blue-Green</li>
  <li>Red-Blue</li>
  <li>Full Spectrum</li>
</ul>

